            <h1>Architecture Description Languages (ADL's)</h1>
          

  <blockquote>
    <blockquote>
<i>Architecture is a broad concept, and each project/domain's
notion of what an architecture is and what sorts of data it should
contain is different (and rightly so!)  Furthermore, the purpose of an architecture
description is largely driven by project stakeholders and their needs.
Thus, no one ADL will ever fit all projects or domains.</i> <b> &mdash;</b> <a href="http://www.ics.uci.edu/%7Eedashofy/"><b>Eric M. Dashofy</b></a></blockquote>
  </blockquote>
  <h2><a name="Concepts"></a>Concepts</h2>
  <blockquote>
    <p><b>Architecture Description Languages (ADLs) describe principal architecture design decisions</b>. Traditionally this has included a system's components, connectors, and configuration.</p>
    <p><b>A large number of <i>domain-specific</i> and general-purpose ADLs have been published</b> and are used in various areas with focus on specific architectural issues: <a href="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/%7Eacme/" target="_blank">ACME</a> focuses on architectural interchange, <a href="http://pavg.stanford.edu/rapide/" target="_blank">Rapide</a> focuses on simulation, and <a href="http://www.htc.honeywell.com/projects/dssa/dssa_tools.html" target="_blank">Meta-H</a> focuses on including hardware concepts, there are many others.</p>
    <p><b>However, a single ADL will <i>never</i> fit all projects or domains. </b>Architecture is a broad concept, and each project/domain's notion of what an architecture is and what sorts of data it should contain is different (and rightly so!) Furthermore, the purpose of an architecture description is largely driven by project stakeholders and their needs.</p>
  </blockquote>

  <h2><a name="Techniques"></a>Techniques</h2>
  <blockquote>
    <p><a href="http://www.isr.uci.edu/projects/xarchuci/way.html"><b>Modularize ADLs</b></a>. Embracing the fact that no single ADL will ever fit all projects or domains, use an ADL that will support controlled, verifiable extension to express new concepts and concerns.</p>
    <p><b><a href="http://www.isr.uci.edu/projects/xarchuci/way.html">Utilize XML for modeling the architecture of software systems</a></b>. Utilizing XML provides unprecedented extensibility and flexibility, as well as basic support from the many available commercial XML tools.</p>
  </blockquote>

  <h2><a name="Notations"></a>Notations</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><b><a href="http://www.isr.uci.edu/projects/xarchuci/">xADL 2.0</a></b>  an extensible and flexible XML-based ADL. xADL 2.0 ships with a number of predefined <a href="http://www.isr.uci.edu/projects/xarchuci/ext-overview.html">xADL 2.0 Schema</a>, or may be extended by your own schema to express the concepts important to your project. </li>
    <li> <a href="xarch/" target="_blank">xArch</a> <i>[LEGACY]</i> a standard, extensible XML-based representation for software architectures.</li>
    <li><a href="adl/SADL.html">C2 SADL</a> <i>[LEGACY]</i> a language for defining architectures built according to the <a href="c2.html">C2 style</a></li>
  </ul>
  <h2><a name="Tools"></a>Tools</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="http://www.isr.uci.edu/projects/xarchuci/tools-apigen.html"><b>Apigen</b></a> - XML schema-to-Java data binding generator for xArch schemas</li>
  </ul>
  <h2><a name="See Also"></a>See Also</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="http://www.isr.uci.edu/projects/xarchuci/way.html">The xADL 2.0 Way</a></li>
